  "prompt": "Does water exist on mars?",
  "response": "Yes, there is evidence that water exists on Mars, primarily in the form of ice. Mars has polar ice caps composed of water and carbon dioxide ice. Additionally, there are signs that liquid water may exist transiently under the surface or during specific conditions, and there are recurring slope lineae (RSL) that suggest the possibility of briny liquid water flowing in some areas. NASA missions and other studies have provided significant insights into the presence and behavior of water on the Martian surface. However, any liquid water that does exist on Mars is likely to be very salty and unstable, making it challenging for life as we know it to survive there.",
